{{Other uses}}
[[File:Feuerbach symposium.jpg|thumb|This painting by [[Anselm Feuerbach]] re-imagines a scene from [[Plato]]'s ''[[Symposium (Plato)|Symposium]]'', in which the tragedian Agathon welcomes the drunken [[Alcibiades]] into his home. 1869.]]

'''Agathon''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|æ|g|ə|θ|ɒ|n}}; {{lang-grc|Ἀγάθων}}; {{circa|448|400 BC}}) was an [[Athens|Athenian]] tragic poet whose works have been lost.  He is best known for his appearance in [[Plato]]'s ''[[Symposium (Plato)|Symposium]],'' which describes the [[Symposium|banquet]] given to celebrate his obtaining a prize for his first [[tragedy]] at the [[Lenaia]] in 416.<ref name="EB1911">{{EB1911|inline=1|wstitle=Agathon|volume=1|page=371}}</ref>  He is also a prominent character in [[Aristophanes]]' comedy the ''[[Thesmophoriazusae]]''.
